# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 0-0-1-3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] One drink per hour is approximately the amount the body can metabolize.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Three drinks per night was selected as a target below the amounts recognized by NIAAA as binge drinking (4 drinks for women, 5 drinks per men).
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] In both national research and at FE Warren rates of injuries, assaults, criminal behavior and other problems increase dramatically with binge drinking.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] The first tier included screening of all personnel for binge drinking utilizing a measure such as the Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT).
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Persons identified as possibly at risk were offered an alcohol screening consultation with the Alcohol and Drug Abuse Prevention and Treatment (ADAPT) program.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Consistent with Air Force policy all active duty members who had alcohol-related misconduct incidents were also referred for evaluation.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Based on evaluation results individuals were provided educational and motivational enhancement interventions, or if found to have a substance use disorder, entered into a treatment program.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] This included development of the name 0-0-1-3 as both a slogan and a guideline for low risk alcohol use.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Personnel from the age range at highest risk for binge drinking, 18-25, were involved in development and execution of these actions.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Metrics collected in 2005 showed a "74% decrease in alcohol-related incidents such as driving violations, public drunkenness, domestic violence, sexual assault, thefts, and other infractions.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] The base also reported 81% fewer cases of underage drinking and 45% fewer drunken-driving arrests." Multiple other military bases adopted elements of the program including a grant-funded trials at five bases.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] The program served as the model for the Air Force's Culture of Responsible Choices (CoRC) program.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] A **0-0-1-3** program was also implemented by the senior administration of the United States Naval Academy in response to a string of alcohol-related incidents that generated a large amount of negative publicity during the 2005-2006 school year.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Its primary aim there is to "promote responsible alcohol use" within the brigade of midshipmen.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] While the senior leadership at the Naval Academy insists that 0-0-1-3 is only a guideline for responsible alcohol use, its enforcement involves mandatory, random breathalyzer tests for all midshipmen regardless of age or rank.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Those found in "violation" of 0-0-1-3 (evidenced by having a BAC above 0.08) are placed on record as having alcohol abuse issues, and repeat offenders are subject to severe administrative infractions, up to and including expulsion.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Military Academy (West Point) nor the U.S.
[src:0-0-1-3/0-0-1-3] Air Force Academy conducts random breathalyzers or punishes students simply for blowing above a particular BAC when not driving a motor vehicle.
[src:0-0-1-3/abuse-prevention-program] An **abuse prevention program** is a social program designed to help parents and teachers recognize the signs of violence in an abused child and teaches how to explain abuse protection to them.
[src:0-0-1-3/abuse-prevention-program] These programs also help children in establishing self-esteem.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Serious side effects include allergic reactions, abnormal heart rhythms, and low or high blood pressure, while less serious side effects include headaches, insomnia, and impotence.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Diarrhea is the most common side effect.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It is unclear if use is safe during pregnancy.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate is useful when used along with counseling in the treatment of alcohol use disorder.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Over three to twelve months it increases the number of people who do not drink at all and the number of days without alcohol.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It appears to work as well as naltrexone for maintenance of abstinence from alcohol, however naltrexone works slightly better for reducing alcohol cravings and heavy drinking, and acamprosate tends to work more poorly outside of Europe where treatment services are less robust.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Difference in severity may also play a role.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Some struggle to take the full course of medication (2 tablets, 3 times a day), which makes acamprosate less effective.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Standard support to help people take their medication involves monthly check-ins with addiction services or a GP.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Research found that compared to standard support alone, extra telephone support by a pharmacist, plus financial incentives, increased the number of people who took medication as prescribed and was cost-effective.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The same telephone support without financial incentives did not significantly increase the number of people taking their medication as prescribed and was less cost-effective.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate is primarily removed by the kidneys.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] A dose reduction is suggested in those with moderately impaired kidneys (creatinine clearance between 30 mL/min and 50 mL/min).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It is also contraindicated in those who have a strong allergic reaction to acamprosate calcium or any of its components.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The US label carries warnings about increases in suicidal behavior, depression, and kidney failure.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Adverse effects that caused people to stop taking the drug in clinical trials included diarrhea, nausea, depression, and anxiety.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The pharmacodynamics of acamprosate are complex and not fully understood.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Ethanol (alcohol) acts on the central nervous system by binding to the GABAA receptor, increasing the effects of the inhibitory neurotransmitter GABA (i.e., it acts as positive allosteric modulators at these receptors).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] In alcohol use disorder, one of the main mechanisms of tolerance is attributed to GABAA receptors becoming downregulated (i.e., these receptors become less sensitive to GABA).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] In addition, alcohol also inhibits the activity of NMDA receptors (NMDARs).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Chronic alcohol consumption leads to the overproduction (upregulation) of these receptors.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Thereafter, sudden alcohol abstinence causes the excessive numbers of NMDARs to be more active than normal and to contribute to the symptoms of delirium tremens and excitotoxic neuronal death.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Withdrawal from alcohol induces a surge in release of excitatory neurotransmitters like glutamate, which activates NMDARs.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate reduces this glutamate surge.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The drug also protects cultured cells from excitotoxicity induced by alcohol withdrawal and from glutamate exposure combined with ethanol withdrawal.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Although its ability to correct an overabundance of glutamate is well-established, the actual molecular target behind this action is poorly known.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Knowledge on this topic has seen several major revisions.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate is originally believed to act as an NMDA receptor antagonist and positive allosteric modulator of GABAA receptors.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The activity of acamprosate on those receptors is indirect, unlike that of most other agents used in this context.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] An inhibition of the GABA-B system is believed to cause indirect enhancement of GABAA receptors.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The effects on the NMDA complex are dose-dependent; the product appears to enhance receptor activation at low concentrations, while inhibiting it when consumed in higher amounts, which counters the excessive activation of NMDA receptors in the context of alcohol withdrawal.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] However, no direct action of acamprosate at clinically relevant concentrations has yet been reported.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] At clinical levels, any inhibition of the NMDA receptor probably occurs in an allosteric way.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] One of acamprosate's purported mechanisms of action is the enhancement of GABA signaling at GABAA receptors via positive allosteric receptor modulation.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It has been purported to open the chloride ion channel in a novel way as it does not require GABA as a cofactor, making it less liable for dependence than benzodiazepines.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate has been successfully used to control tinnitus, hyperacusis, ear pain, and inner ear pressure during alcohol use due to spasms of the tensor tympani muscle.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Two later hypothesized targets are mGluR1 and mGluR5 (10 μM).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The idea originated from the fact that acamprosate blocked the neurotoxicity of an agonist of mGluR1 and mGluR5.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] However, a subsequent study found no action of acamprosate on the mGluR1 or mGluR5 at concentrations as high as 100 μM, nor at GABAA or glycine receptors or voltage-gated sodium channels.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] In addition, even if the 10 μM figure is correct, it would still be clinically irrelevant.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] (2014) show that the effects of acamprosate calcium can mostly be attributed to the calcium component.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Replacing calcium with sodium produces an inactive drug.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Calcium chloride has a similar effect on glutamate neurotransmission.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Moreover, calcium carbonate has a similar craving-reducing effect on human alcoholics.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] (2023) report that acamprosate sodium does, in fact, enhance the effect of calcium chloride in an animal alcoholism model, and hence is not a fully inactive molecule.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] They also show a role of increased dopamine levels in the nucleus accumbe downstream of the glycine receptor, partly mimicking ethanol.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The product also increases the endogenous production of taurine.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The substance also helps re-establish a standard sleep architecture by normalizing stage 3 and REM sleep phases, which is believed to be an important aspect of its pharmacological activity.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate is not metabolized by the human body.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate's absolute bioavailability from oral administration is approximately 11%, and its bioavailability is decreased when taken with food.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Following administration and absorption of acamprosate, it is excreted unchanged (i.e., as acamprosate) via the kidneys.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Co-administration with naltrexone increases plasma levels.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Its absorption and elimination are very slow, with a *t*max of 6 hours and an elimination half life of over 30 hours.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Steady-state levels are reached by day 5 of oral treatment.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate was developed by Lipha, a subsidiary of Merck KGaA. and was approved for marketing in Europe in 1989.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] In October 2001 Forest Laboratories acquired the rights to market the drug in the US.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It was approved by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in July 2004.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The first generic versions of acamprosate were launched in the US in 2013.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] As of 2015, acamprosate was in development by Confluence Pharmaceuticals as a potential treatment for fragile X syndrome.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] The drug was granted orphan drug designation for this use by the FDA in 2013, and by the European Medicines Agency (EMA) in 2014.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate is the International Nonproprietary Name (INN) and the British Approved Name (BAN).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] Acamprosate calcium is the United States Adopted Name (USAN) and the Japanese Accepted Name (JAN).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It is also technically known as *N*-acetylhomotaurine or as calcium acetylhomotaurinate.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It is sold under the brand name Campral.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] In addition to its apparent ability to help people refrain from drinking, some evidence suggests that acamprosate is neuroprotective (that is, it protects neurons from damage and death caused by the effects of alcohol withdrawal, and possibly other causes of neurotoxicity).
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It has been tried for autism, both idiopathic and fragile X syndrome-linked.
[src:0-0-1-3/acamprosate] It appears to reduce amyloid-beta precursor protein levels.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Physicians specializing in the field are in general agreement concerning applicability of treatment to those with addiction to drugs, such as alcohol and heroin, and often also to gambling, which has similar characteristics and has been well-described in the scientific literature.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] There is less agreement concerning definition or treatment of other so-called addictive behaviors such as sexual addiction and internet addiction, such behaviors not being marked generally by physiologic tolerance or withdrawal.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Over centuries, addiction has been recognized as an issue to be treated, and has been addressed with the creation of a multitude of organizations, the passage of certain acts, and the development of various drugs in the medical field all to help those who struggle with addiction.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Doctors focusing on addiction medicine are medical specialists who focus on addictive disease and have had special study and training focusing on the prevention and treatment of such diseases.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] There are two routes to specialization in the addiction field: one via a psychiatric pathway and one via other fields of medicine.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The American Society of Addiction Medicine notes that approximately 40% of its members are psychiatrists (MD/DO) while the remainder have received primary medical training in other fields.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Addiction first became well known and seen as a major issue between the 1750s and early 1800s with alcoholism running rampant and being the main contributor to this.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Benjamin Rush first began to discern alcoholism as an illness to be addressed when he published his writing “*Inquiry into the Effects of Ardent Spirits on the Human Mind and Body*” in 1784.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Because of his writing on alcoholism, the beginnings of the temperance movement came shortly after in the early 1800s.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The first inebriate homes for alcoholics opened around the 1850s.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] These homes and asylums provided a segregated place for alcoholics to stay while they withdrew from the alcohol, along with integration into sobriety groups.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Joseph Edward Turner opened the New York State Inebriate Asylum, which was the first rehabilitation center for alcoholism.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In the late 1800s, around 1890, alcoholics were sent to hospital wards and drunk tanks as inebriate homes began shutting down.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Throughout the first half of the 1900s, many hospitals and organizations opened to assist addicts, such as the Charles B.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Towns substance abuse Hospital (1901), the Emmanuel Clinic/the Emmanuel movement (1906), morphine maintenance clinics (1919–1924), narcotics farms (1935), Alcoholics Anonymous (1935), etc.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In addition to this, certain state laws were passed to try to sterilize disabled people, addicts, and people with mental disorders (1910).
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] During this time, various drugs also came out to attempt to cure alcoholism like barbiturates, amphetamines, LSD, and disulfiram (1948–1950).
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Within these years, multiple advancements were made, certain laws or acts were passed, and more organizations came about to help people with addiction.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In 1957, treatment units for alcoholics were developed by the Veterans Administration.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Shortly thereafter, a multitude of associations opened.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] These include but are not limited to the Halfway House Association (1958), the Betty Ford Clinic (1982), Cocaine Anonymous (1982), Secular Organizations for Sobriety and Rational Recovery (1985–1986), and SMART Recovery (1994).
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Along with that, drugs like methadone (1964), Narcan (1971), and naltrexone (1994) were developed to fight against opioid withdrawal and alcoholism.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] As for the legal side of things, the Controlled Substances Act passed in 1970, which classified all controlled substances into five classes, and the Drug Addiction Treatment Act passed in 1999, enforcing a stricter version of the Controlled Substances Act.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In the past 25 years, further developments have been made in the field of addiction medicine such as the FDA approval of a treatment called buprenorphine for opioid use disorder, along with The Mental Health Parity and Addiction Equity Act (2008) and the Affordable Care Act (2010) being passed.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The MHPAEA of 2008 made it mandatory for insurance organizations to give people coverage for the cost of substance-abuse-related treatments, while the ACA of 2010 further expanded the coverage offered for substance-abuse-related treatments through state health insurances.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In several countries around the world, specialist bodies have been set up to ensure high quality practice in addiction medicine.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] In October 2015, the American Board of Medical Specialties (ABMS) officially recognized addiction medicine as a subspecialty.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Within the United States, there are two accepted specialty examinations.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] One is a Board Certification in Addiction Psychiatry from the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The other is a Board Certification in Addiction Medicine from the American Board of Preventive Medicine.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The latter approach is available to all physicians with primary Board certification, while the former is available only to board-certified psychiatrists.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Doctors of Osteopathic Medicine may also seek board certification via the American Osteopathic Association (AOA).
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine must have a primary board certification in Neurology & Psychiatry, Internal Medicine, or Family Practice from the American Osteopathic Association and complete an AOA approved addiction medicine fellowship.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Successful completion of a board examination administered via the AOA will grant a certificate of added qualification (CAQ) in addiction medicine.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] Within Australia, addiction medicine specialists are certified via the Chapter of Addiction Medicine, which is part of the Royal Australasian College of Physicians.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] They may alternatively be a member of the Section of Addiction Psychiatry, Royal Australian & New Zealand College of Psychiatrists.
[src:0-0-1-3/addiction-medicine] The International Society of Addiction Medicine also can provide certification of expertise.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] License suspension or revocation traditionally follows conviction for alcohol-impaired or drunk driving.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] Because ALS laws are immediate and require no proof of guilt, proponents such as Mothers Against Drunk Driving argue that they are more effective in reducing drunk driving than are traditional post-conviction sanctions, and that, in any event, driving is only a privilege.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The laws have also been criticized as constituting double jeopardy and/or multiple punishment.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] While the argument for double jeopardy is tenuous, that for multiple punishment may have merit: the driver has his license suspended by the State in the ALS proceedings, and then is punished by the State again in court for the same offense—the punishment often involving a second license suspension.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] While this issue has been resolved both ways in the past by state and federal courts, the currently prevailing view is that there is no multiple punishment since the suspension is only an administrative "sanction", not a criminal "punishment".
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] As of 2010, only nine states did not have ALS laws: Kentucky, Michigan, Montana, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Carolina, South Dakota and Tennessee.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] In the state of Texas, Administrative License Revocation is a process by which an individual who is arrested for Driving While Intoxicated (DWI) has his or her driver's license administratively suspended.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] This program went into effect on January 1, 1995, and is administrated by the Texas Department of Public Safety (DPS).
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] DPS records indicate that 103,168 notices of suspension were served during the calendar year 2003.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] During that period, the agency processed 95,495 suspensions.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] A suspension can occur from either the refusal to submit to a chemical test or results of 0.08 or greater alcohol concentration when a chemical test is taken.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] This blood alcohol concentration (0.08 grams percent) applies to drivers aged 21 and over, but a lower BAC level applies to underage drivers or any driver operating a commercial motor vehicle.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] DPS is also authorized to suspend the drivers licenses of minors who commit the offense of driving under the influence (DUI) as well as individuals who refuse to provide a specimen following an arrest for the offense of boating while intoxicated (BWI).
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The statutes concerning ALS are found in the Texas Transportation Code at Chapters 524 and 724.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The administrative license suspension process usually begins when a law enforcement officer determines that there is reasonable suspicion for an initial traffic stop of a motorist.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] If the officer has reason to believe that the driver is impaired, field sobriety tests are administered.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] If the driver performs poorly, the driver is arrested for DWI and transported to the police station.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] At the station, the officer will read to the driver the "Statutory Warning" and then request that driver submit to a breath or blood test to measure his/her alcohol concentration.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] If the driver refuses to provide a specimen or provides a specimen with a prohibited alcohol concentration, the officer serves a notice of suspension and confiscates the driver's license.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] Procedures for handling minors vary slightly.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] A law enforcement officer must have reasonable suspicion to conduct a traffic stop, however, a full custodial arrest is not required.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] Once the officer determines that the individual is under 21 years of age and has reason to believe that he/she has consumed alcohol, the officer will issue the driver a citation for DUI, serve the notice of suspension, and confiscate the driver license.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The minor may or may not be placed under arrest and a chemical test may or may not be requested.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The officer may proceed with a custodial arrest procedure if he believes the individual is seriously impaired.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The driver has fifteen days from the date of the notice of suspension is served to request a hearing.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] If no hearing is requested, the suspension will automatically go into effect on the 40th day after notice was served.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The period of suspension is 90 days to a year, depending upon the existence of prior convictions; if a refusal to submit to testing is involved, the periods are 180 days to two years.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] Minors face suspensions of 60 to 180 days.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] Assuming the license holder makes the demand for a hearing within the statutory period, a hearing is scheduled.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The nature of these vary considerably from state to state.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] In some states, the hearing takes place in court before a judge.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] More commonly, however, an administrative hearing will be conducted by the state's Department of Motor Vehicles.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] The procedures for these administrative hearings vary as well.
[src:0-0-1-3/administrative-license-suspension] In some, the hearing will be presided over by an Administrative Law Judge (ALJ), the state's case will be presented by a prosecutor, and the officer will be required to testify.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The organization's name is often ascribed to Janet G.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The term *ACoA* was also extended to include PTSD by Tian Dayton, specifically in her book *The ACoA Trauma Syndrome.* In it she describes how pain from childhood emerges and gets played out in adulthood, for the ACoA, as a post-traumatic stress reaction.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Childhood pain that has remained relatively dormant for decades can be re-stimulated or "triggered" by the dynamics of intimacy.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] ACA/ACOA was originally named "Post Teen" in Mineola, Long Island in 1973.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] In the mid-1970s, a group of older Alateens in Manhattan, a part of the Al-Anon fellowship, formed a group of those who were looking for a group that was not focused on parental or spousal relationships with those dealing with alcohol substance abuse.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] They called this group Hope of Adult Children of Alcoholics.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] After being asked to speak on his experiences in Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) and Al-Anon to this group, Tony A. joined as a member.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] When fewer people were in attendance, Tony A. opened up the group to AA members who were adult children.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Eventually, Tony started a co-current group called Generations which was not affiliated with any twelve-step group.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] In 1978 Tony A. wrote *The Laundry List* (the 14 characteristics of adult children) and the *Solution* and shared it with his Generations group.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The meeting where Tony A. shared his *Laundry List* is considered the beginning of ACA/ACOA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Members of "Generations" expressed discomfort with the AA steps around this time and also declined an offer to become an official Al-Anon group in the 1980s.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Tony A. began working on a version of the 12 steps specifically for adult children of alcoholics, and published them in his 1991 book, *The Laundry List: The ACOA Experience* that he wrote with Dan F.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Currently, ACA allows use of Tony A.'s 12 steps in addition to the AA-based 12 steps formally in ACA-approved literature.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] This 12-step program is incorporated as Adult Children of Alcoholics/Dysfunctional Families.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The ACA framework is based on the 12 steps and 12 traditions of AA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] During the 1990s, the organization went through rapid growth.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] In 1989, there were 1,300 ACA meetings and by 2003 there were an estimated 40,000 members of ACA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] In 2014, there were 1,300 groups worldwide, about 780 of these in the USA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Although this isn't the full picture, as of November 3, 2024, globally there are 2,745 ACA meetings registered with ACA World Services.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] ACA is organized along the lines of 12 steps and 12 traditions adopted by the ACA World Service Organization ACA meetings are formed without leaders and are maintained by group conscience and following the 12 steps of ACA/Tony A and traditions of ACA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Meetings are held with the principle of anonymity for members online, via phone, or in-person.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] "The vast majority of ACAs meet informally, in school classrooms or church halls, in the evenings or over weekends.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Few frequent expensive treatment centres.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] They are sympathetic to, but not part of, the AA movement.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] They meet in leaderless groups, pooling their resources of experience and insight, and reading relevant literature to deepen those assets.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] For an ACA, this support group provides the extended family and unconditional support which he or she never experienced.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The group further provides practical help in acquiring everyday interpersonal and coping skills, and, with them, the sense of self-efficacy—a basic need, as Peele says.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The group also provides a sense of community, a community of interest which there are few neighbourhood groups nowadays to provide.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] This sense of community is another basic need, as Peele argues.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Membership comes from a felt need, not as a life sentence.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The goal of working the program is emotional sobriety.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] In 2006, ACA published a fellowship text of 646 pages, describing in details what the program is and how it works.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] This text is also called "The Big Red Book", mirroring the AA fellowship text being called "The Big Book" by members of AA.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] ACA is more of a therapeutic program which emphasizes taking care of the self and reparenting one's own wounded inner child with love rather than focusing on one source of substance abuse (though members may or may not have substance abuse issues) as in other 12-step groups.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] It aims to build oneself up, assumes personal responsibility by unequivocally standing up for one's right to a healthy life and actively works on the changes necessary to achieving it.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The collective stance is not to wallow in "being a victim" but to move into the practical application of seeing family dysfunction as a generational affliction and a pattern that can be healed.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Through fellowship and the support of ACA's sponsors and peers, as well as the literature, members come to learn that even the most wounded of them has an inner child worthy of love and healing.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] The crux of the community and its mindfulness comes from honest accounts of struggles and sincere compassion towards these.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] ACA does not rely heavily on a traditional "sponsor" format as in AA, although some may follow this format in ACA, but favors a "Fellow Traveler" approach that emphasizes learning from each other as you both work the program.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] ACA offers a program to recover from the effects of growing up in an alcoholic or otherwise dysfunctional family.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] It is not affiliated with AA, but it follows the 12-step structure and format of groups based on Alcoholics Anonymous.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] It features 12 steps adapted from the AA steps and 12 steps authored by co-founder, Tony A.
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] (which have not been conference approved by the ACA WSO).
[src:0-0-1-3/adult-children-of-alcoholics] Woititz, author of *Adult Children of Alcoholics*, endorsed the ACA.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon defines itself as an independent fellowship with the stated purpose of helping relatives and friends of alcoholics.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] According to the organization, alcoholism is a family illness.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Not an intervention program, Al-Anon does not have the stated primary purpose of arresting another's compulsive drinking.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Meetings are usually small (five to twenty-five); in larger meetings, members often split into smaller groups after the opening readings so everyone has a chance to speak.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon was co-founded in 1951, 16 years after the founding of Alcoholics Anonymous on June 10, 1935, by Anne B. and Lois W.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Before the formation of Al-Anon, independent groups of families of alcoholics met.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon adopted the Twelve Steps of Alcoholics Anonymous for their own use, changing the word "alcoholics" in the twelfth step to "others" ("we tried to carry this message to others").
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Its name derives from the first parts of the words "Alcoholics Anonymous".
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Although people commonly turn to Al-Anon for help in stopping another's drinking, the organization recognizes that the friends and families of alcoholics are often traumatized themselves and in need of emotional support and understanding.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The Al-Anon program takes the focus away from the alcoholic and redirects it to the loved one.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] By working the 12 Steps, individuals can work on themselves and the ways that the family disease of alcoholism has changed their own thinking, opposed to the unsuccessful attempts of changing the alcoholic.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The fellowship believes that after so long of living and loving an alcoholic, the loved ones take on blame, hurt, and the guilt of the alcoholic, in turn becoming ill too.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The purpose is to have a community in which the loved one can share experience, strength, and hope aiding in solving common problems, not fixing the alcoholic.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon/Alateen literature focuses on problems common to family members and friends of alcoholics such as excessive care-taking, an inability to differentiate between love versus pity and loyalty to abusers, rather than the problems of the alcoholic.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The organization acknowledges that members may join with low self-esteem, largely a side-effect of unrealistically overestimating their agency and control: attempting to control another person's drinking behavior and, when they fail, blaming themselves for the other person's behavior.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Participation in Al-Anon has been associated with less personal blame by women who, as a whole, engage in more initial personal blame for the drinking than men.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Family members of alcoholics begin to improve as they learn to recognize family pathology, assign responsibility for the pathology to a disease, forgive themselves, accept that they were adversely affected by the pathology and learn to accept their family members' shortcomings.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon members are encouraged to keep the focus on themselves, rather than on the alcoholic.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Although members believe that changed attitudes can aid recovery, they stress that one person did not cause, cannot cure and cannot control another person's alcohol-related choices and behaviors.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon's primary purpose is to help families and friends of alcoholics, rather than stopping alcoholism in others or assisting with interventions.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] When an alcoholic's spouse is active in Al-Anon and the alcoholic is active in AA, the alcoholic is more likely to be abstinent, marital happiness is more likely to be increased and parenting by both is more likely to improve.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] A 1999 clinical analysis of methods used by concerned significant others (CSOs) to encourage alcoholics to seek treatment indicated that Al-Anon participation was "mostly ineffective" towards this goal.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The psychologists found community reinforcement approach and family training (CRAFT) "significantly more" effective than Al-Anon participation in arresting alcoholism in others.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] In 2015, Al-Anon Family Groups published its *2015 Member Survey Results* of demographic and other information from Al-Anon members in Canada and the United States Of the 8,517 respondents, 93 percent identified as white, 83 percent as female and 61 percent as married.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Twelve percent of the respondents had children under age 18 at home, while "80 percent of respondents have been in a romantic relationship involving an alcoholic partner".
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] And one side finding was that "40 percent of respondents initially joined Al-Anon because a person with a drug problem was negatively affecting their lives".
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] For the *2006 Alateen Member Survey*, conducted in the U.S., 139 Alateen members responded.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Sixty-five percent of the respondents were female, 35 percent were male, 72 percent were white and 20 percent spoke Spanish fluently.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The structure of Al-Anon Family Groups may be depicted as an inverted pyramid, with the organization's headquarters (the World Service Office) at the bottom and the "autonomous" groups at the top.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon and Alateen members meet in Groups for fellowship and support.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Each Group may elect a Group Representative (GR) to represent a group at District meetings.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon and Alateen Groups' Group Representatives (GRs) attend District meetings.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] At these meetings they discuss service activities, Group issues (their primary purpose being to be a forum for Groups) and information from their Area and the World Service Office (WSO) of Al-Anon and Alateen, with GRs having voting privileges.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] A District may host regular events, such as workshops and speaker meetings, for the local fellowship.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] (For example, Texas is divided into two Al-Anon and Alateen Areas, East and West.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] At Area Assembly, GRs elect a Delegate to the annual World Service Conference (WSC) (aka "The Conference").
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The WSC meets annually to interface with the World Service Office (WSO), which is managed by administrators and overseen by the Board of Trustees (who meet more regularly themselves).
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] Al-Anon promotes democracy and accountability.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The World Service Office (WSO) is accountable to the World Service Conference (WSC).
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The WSC is responsible to the Areas through elected Delegates and ultimately responsible to the Groups.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The 1994 film *When a Man Loves a Woman* "...confronts the realities of substance abuse as it affects all members of one family with an alcoholic at its center." The alcoholic is played by Meg Ryan and her husband, who makes his way to an Al-Anon meeting, is played by Andy García.
[src:0-0-1-3/al-anon-alateen] The hosts of Beyond Belief Sobriety discuss the film in a 2019 podcast episode.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] An **alcohol-free zone**, or **dry zone**, is a geographic area, location or establishment where the public consumption and sale of alcoholic beverages is prohibited.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Alcohol-free zones have been established in some areas to address problems with drinking- and binge drinking-related crime, antisocial behavior, assaults and disorderly behavior.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] In New South Wales, Australia, some streets are designated as alcohol-free zones, which is demarcated with signage stating such.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Police may issue a warning to violators, and those who continue to drink can be fined and have their alcoholic beverages seized.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Many parks in New South Wales are designated as alcohol-free zones.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Bondi in New South Wales, Australia established an alcohol-free zone in the city in 2004 in efforts to reduce assaults and antisocial behavior influenced by street drinking.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] As of April 2016, Sydney, Australia has over 60 alcohol-free zones.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The City Council of Sydney proposed to eliminate the alcohol-free zones in April 2016.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Alcohol-free zone networks have been established in areas of Azerbaijan since at least 1996.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] These zones are located in areas such as cafes, tea shops and recreation centers.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The first alcohol-free zone established in the United Kingdom was in Coventry, England in 1988.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Initially, the entire city center was declared to be an alcohol-free zone.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The zone was later expanded to include the entire city.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Boston, Lincolnshire established a street drinking ban in January 2015 to address concerns with the antisocial problems associated with public alcohol consumption.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The street drinking ban includes the town center and other areas.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Under rules of the ban, those caught drinking in these areas can be fined £100 for a first offense.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] A second offense within six months after having committed a first one can be fined up to £500.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Additionally, those that are requested to stop drinking and continue to do so can receive a fine of up to £500.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] In January 2015 to commemorate the event, various town council members and city police attended an event where cans of beer were poured down a city street drain.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] In 2009, Knowsley, Merseyside established alcohol-free zones in some of its parks to address problems with binge drinking-related crime and antisocial behavior.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Drinking in licensed drinking establishments was not affected by the zones.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Liverpool, England has some alcohol-free zones in areas of the city.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The entire region of Attappadi, Kerala, India was established as an alcohol-free zone in 1996 by Chief Minister AK Antony.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Despite the ban, alcohol has been illegally brought into the region by community residents who travel to Annaikatti to purchase liquor from TASMAC stores.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Gujarat, the state of india is totally alcohol free from decades.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] Some parks and recreation areas in the United States are alcohol-free zones, such as in Johnson County, Iowa, where alcohol consumption is allowed in some park and recreation areas but not others.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] For example, alcoholic beverages may be consumed in some day use areas and campgrounds in parks, but not in beach areas within some parks.
[src:0-0-1-3/alcohol-free-zone] The riverfront at Covington, Kentucky was established as an alcohol-free zone circa 1989 by Covington police.
